ce:section.ce:para:
The pore size characteristics of the prepared CDs@ZIF-L were investigated by N2 adsorption–desorption (Fig. 4
                        b) and the CDs@ZIF-L composites exhibited a typical type I adsorption isotherm and a sharp increase in nitrogen adsorption was observed at low pressure (P/P0 < 0.1), which indicates that the material has a typical microporous structure [39]. Compared to ZIF-L (26.849 m2/g) CDs@ZIF-L had a larger specific surface area (27.374 m2/g) with a total pore volume of 0.082 cm3/g and a pore size of 11.709 nm (Table 2
                        ), demonstrating that the higher BET specific surface area and smaller pore size of the composite may have a stronger adsorption capacity.
